sentence-detokenized: Cricket - Leicestershire take over at the top after innings win
West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons picked up 38 runs on Friday as Leicestershire took over the county title after beating Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days.
Their peak form may be short-lived, however, as title rivals Essex, Derby County and Surrey all move closer to victory, while Kent make up for lost time in a rain-soaked clash with Nottinghamshire.

After bowling Somerset out for 83 in the opening session at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296, with England outcast Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Trailing by 213 runs, Somerset made a solid start to the second innings before Simmons stepped in to bundle them out for 174.
However, Essex looked certain to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Sooke took firm control of their positions in Headingley's clash with Yorkshire.
Hussain, considered surplus to requirements for England's one-dayers, hit 158, his first winning century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.

At the close, Yorkshire had converted that advantage into 37 runs, but off-spinner Sooke spoiled their hopes by taking four for 24 off 48 balls, leaving them hanging there on 119 for five and praying for rain.
At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another England outcast, continued to silence his critics as he followed up his 45-run game on Thursday with an 80-run no out against Warwickshire on Friday.
He was supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who closed on 429 for 7 at Surrey, leading by 234 runs.
Derbyshire continued their pursuit of their first title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in the second innings, 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australian Tom Moody took six for 82 but Chris Adams and Tim O'Gorman scored 109 to take Derbyshire to 471 for a first innings lead of 233.
After the frustration of seeing their first day of the tournament severely affected by the weather, Kent upped a gear and knocked Nottinghamshire out for 214.
They were held off by Paul Johnson's 84, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague took four for 55.
By the time of the stumps, Kent had reached 108 for 3.

Alan Shearer, the world's most expensive footballer, was appointed as the new England captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old joins Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), replacing Tony Adams and former captain David Platt who led the team during the European Championships in June.
Adams and Pratt are both injured and will miss England's World Cup qualifying opener against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer is captaining the side on a trial basis but new coach Glenn Hoddle says he sees no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain can't make the position his own.
"I'm sure there will be no problem, I'm sure Alan is the man for the job," Hodel said.
"There are three or four people who could do it, but when I spoke to Alan he was keen to do it and really wanted to do it.
"It's hard to come to 100% conclusions about something like this in four days ......
But he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the team, even though he plays up front."
Shearer's striking partner in Euro 96, Teddy Sheringham, withdrew from the squad on Friday due to injury.
He could be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

Football - Rotor fans locked out after violence in Volgograd

Rotor Volgograd's next home game will have to be played behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat, ending Rotor's brief run as league leaders.
Anatoly Gorokhovsky, head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, said on Friday that Rotor will face an empty stand for the match against Rada Togliatti on September 3.
The club was fined $1,000 after knocking Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position with 11 games to go in the championship.
Volgograd are three points behind Alanya and two behind Dynamo Moscow, who have one game over the leaders and two games over FC Moscow.

This game was to prepare me for it.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer admit that the man who has won titles in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is approaching the end of his career.

Tennis - Tarango, O'Brien up under the lights in a double header
Andre Agassi escaped with a win on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalists Mari Vai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on the night of the U.S. Open upsets.
Eleventh seed Washington failed to repeat his Wimbledon miracle as he lost to red-hot wildcard Alexander O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 after two hours and 51 minutes of struggle on the stadium court.
In the next stand, 10th seed Rios lost to another player with Wimbledon connections - bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The grumpy left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
Although sixth seeded former champion Agassi had to struggle out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole, the day's programme went well as he won 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the rookies.
Washington climbed back from 1-5 down in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals and looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title in New Haven a fortnight ago, served out a 5-4 win in the third set before Washington stormed back.
"I just kept saying to myself, 'Keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting and maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th.
"I kept my composure and I was proud of myself - normally I would have folded up my tent and gone home."
O'Brien, a former U.S. college national champion with a tough service attitude, hit 17 aces to finally subdue a never-say-die Washington team.
The fifth set stayed on serve until the sixth when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner, put a backhand into the net to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan blasted two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point when Washington hit a 40-0 backhand into the net for the win.
"You just kind of keep fighting and you keep trying to get him to play a bit.
I think he was a little nervous at a couple of moments," Washington said."
But I think he served well when he had to."

Tarango, whose Wimbledon tantrum two years ago brought him a $28,000 fine and suspension from this year's tournament at the All England Club, engaged in a lively two-hour and 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands, arguing calls and taunting fans.
Raucous cheers supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American who ate up all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said the 104th-ranked Tarango."
I thought I played really well tonight and was very focused."
The match took a turn for the worse in the deciding game of the third set, which the American won 7-5, much to the dismay of the crowd.
"I like the audience if they boo me every day.
It excites me and makes me play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I played some of my best tennis in college when fraternities threw beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have more fun."
Rios did not appreciate Tarango's antics.
"He always complained too much," Rios said."
But I don't think that's the case.
I think I played very badly.
It's tough to play at night.
I have lost too many points that I never lost.
"I don't see the ball as much as I do during the day.
I play as an American, so that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch."
At the end of the match, Tarango blew a sarcastic kiss to the crowd before shaking his body in salute to Rios' roots amidst jeers.
"I support their passion," Tarango said of the fans."
At the same time, they were openly cheering me on.
After I won, I thought I could give them a little bragging rights."
NFL American Football - Randall Cunningham retires.
Randall Cunningham, the NFL's all-time leading rusher as a quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to play under centre, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham has played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham was a three-time Pro Bowl selection, rushing for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organization and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"While it saddens me to leave, I look forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randle is one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie."
In his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randle has been a cornerstone of the Eagles and has delivered many great moments for fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL."
A second-round selection in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has been signed as a broadcaster.
